{"id": "duc04-testb-45:2#6", "contents": "On Tuesday, a federal district judge agreed to review complaints made by lawyers for three men arrested after the bombings of two U.S. embassies in Africa, stating that their jail conditions in Manhattan are unconstitutional and inhumane. The complaints, outlined in an eight-page letter, alleged that the defendants are being held in total isolation for almost 24 hours a day in a unit called 10 South, the most restrictive holding area in the Metropolitan Correctional Center in lower Manhattan. The defendants are only allowed brief periods of exercise in a barren room, referred to as the \"rat cage.\" Judge Leonard Sand of U.S. District Court in Manhattan agreed to review the conditions, stating that it \"has to be addressed, that is, the condition of confinement for all of the defendants.\""}
